## command-center tools

All ten tools talk to the local Command Center workspace over MCP.

### Read

- `get_workspace` — your primary read. First call in every triage pass.
  Returns stats, active plan items, recent items, attention queue, duplicate
  groups, oldest open items, low-connection backlog, and existing connections.
- `get_attention` — shortcut for just the items needing review.
- `search_items` — lookup by query string or filters (status, category,
  focus_area). Use this when resolving "is this a duplicate?" questions.

### Write

- `update_items` — your primary write. Always batch — pass an array of
  updates, not one per call. Every triage pass should make at most one
  `update_items` call.
- `connect_items` — link two items (establishes a relationship,
  typically `related` or `duplicate`).
- `disconnect_items` — remove a connection.
- `promote_items` — push items to the configured promotion target.
  Only use when the item has a clear owner and next action. Include
  `external_ref`, `external_url`, `owner`, and `evidence` when a real external
  handoff exists.
- `capture_item` — create a new item. Only use when you're capturing
  on behalf of your principal from a conversation or external source,
  not for moving existing items between states.

### Cleanup (weekly only)

- `scan_queue_noise` — runs the full duplicate/stale/heartbeat analysis.
  This is O(n²). Call it weekly, not daily.
- `apply_queue_cleanup` — acts on the output of `scan_queue_noise`.
  Actions: `archive-duplicate-group` (needs `primaryId`),
  `demote-heartbeat-group`, `archive`, `reference`, `delete`.
  Prefer archive over delete.

### Idempotency

All updates take absolute values (set `status`, `disposition`, `focus_area`
directly). Reapplying the same update is a no-op on field values but
refreshes `updated_at`. This is intentional — if a cron pass is interrupted
and retried, the result is the same state.

### Outcome and handoff fields

Use `owner`, `revisit_at`, `decision_needed`, `outcome_status`,
`outcome_note`, `evidence`, and `superseded_by` to close loops. Use
`execution_target`, `execution_ref`, and `execution_url` to record where a
promoted item is being executed.
